Note:
==============================================================================
AES - Advanced Encryption Standard per FIPS 197
==============================================================================

This module implements the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) block cipher
per FIPS PUB 197, the algorithm formerly known as Rijndael selected by NIST
in 2001 as the U.S. federal standard for symmetric-key encryption.

Key sizes supported:
  AES-128:  16-byte key, Nk=4 32-bit words, Nr=10 rounds, 176-byte key schedule
  AES-192:  24-byte key, Nk=6 32-bit words, Nr=12 rounds, 208-byte key schedule
  AES-256:  32-byte key, Nk=8 32-bit words, Nr=14 rounds, 240-byte key schedule

Block size: 16 bytes (128 bits) for all key sizes.

Algorithm (encryption):
  1. AddRoundKey with round-key 0.
  2. For each round r in 1..Nr-1:
       a. SubBytes (apply S-box to each byte)
       b. ShiftRows (cyclically shift rows 1, 2, 3 by 1, 2, 3 positions)
       c. MixColumns (matrix multiply each column by fixed polynomial)
       d. AddRoundKey with round-key r
  3. Final round (no MixColumns):
       a. SubBytes
       b. ShiftRows
       c. AddRoundKey with round-key Nr

Decryption is the inverse: AddRoundKey of round Nr, then for each interior
round InvShiftRows, InvSubBytes, AddRoundKey, InvMixColumns; final round
omits InvMixColumns; AddRoundKey of round 0 finishes.

Side-channel posture:
- Constant-time SubBytes via the "full S-box scan" pattern: every byte
  lookup scans all 256 S-box entries and selects the matching one with
  an arithmetic equality mask (NOT a secret-dependent branch). The
  total time per SubByte is independent of the input byte. Cache-timing
  attacks on the S-box (Bernstein, 2005) are defeated because every
  call touches the same memory pattern regardless of the secret index.

- Constant-time key expansion: SubWord uses the same full-scan S-box.
  The Rcon table is indexed by round number (public, loop-invariant).

- Constant-time GF(2^8) arithmetic: xtime is implemented as
  ((value << 1) ^ ((-(msb_bit)) & 0x1b)) & 0xff, with the masked-XOR
  encoding the conditional reduction. gmul iterates 8 bits and combines
  via arithmetic masks rather than branches.

- No secret-dependent control flow anywhere on the encrypt/decrypt hot
  paths. Loop bounds depend only on Nr (a function of the public key
  size).

CPU acceleration probes:
- aes_supports_hardware_acceleration: x86_64 CPUID leaf 1, ECX bit 25
  (AES-NI).
- aes_supports_pclmulqdq: x86_64 CPUID leaf 1, ECX bit 1 (PCLMULQDQ).
These probes export the runtime capability flags to higher layers
(AES-GCM uses pclmulqdq for the GHASH carry-less-multiply path). The
block functions in THIS module remain on the constant-time software
path so that the FIPS 197 Appendix B and Appendix C Known Answer Tests
validate the same implementation byte-for-byte on every supported
architecture.

References:
- FIPS PUB 197, "Advanced Encryption Standard (AES)", NIST, 26 Nov 2001.
- Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen, "The Design of Rijndael", Springer, 2002.
- Intel Corporation, "Intel Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) New
  Instructions Set", Rev 3.01, September 2012.
- Daniel J. Bernstein, "Cache-timing attacks on AES", 2005.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena

Constant AES_BLOCK_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant AES128_KEY_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant AES192_KEY_SIZE as Integer is 24
Constant AES256_KEY_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant AES128_ROUNDS as Integer is 10
Constant AES192_ROUNDS as Integer is 12
Constant AES256_ROUNDS as Integer is 14
Constant AES128_SCHEDULE_SIZE as Integer is 176
Constant AES192_SCHEDULE_SIZE as Integer is 208
Constant AES256_SCHEDULE_SIZE as Integer is 240
Constant AES128_NK as Integer is 4
Constant AES192_NK as Integer is 6
Constant AES256_NK as Integer is 8

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CPU feature detection (x86_64 CPUID leaf 1, ECX flags)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_supports_hardware_acceleration" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reports whether the executing x86_64 CPU advertises the AES-NI
    instruction-set extension (AESENC, AESENCLAST, AESDEC, AESDECLAST,
    AESKEYGENASSIST, AESIMC). Higher layers may use this signal to
    select an accelerated AEAD or KEM path that emits the AES-NI
    instructions directly via inline assembly.

    On non-x86_64 platforms the inline assembly is replaced with a noop
    at codegen and the initializer-zero result is returned.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Executes CPUID leaf 1:
      eax = 1
      cpuid
      AES-NI present iff (ecx >> 25) & 1 == 1
    Writes the bit into the local frame slot for result and returns it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    CPUID is ~100 cycles. Far below the cost of any single AES block,
    so callers can invoke this on every cryptographic operation without
    caching, though caching across the process lifetime is also safe.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No secret-dependent control flow. The CPUID output is a public
    property of the CPU model.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # CPUID leaf 1: AES-NI bit = ECX bit 25
        mov rax, 1
        cpuid
        shr rcx, 25
        and rcx, 1
        mov [rbp-8], rcx
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "aes_supports_pclmulqdq" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Reports whether the executing x86_64 CPU advertises the PCLMULQDQ
    instruction (carry-less 64x64 multiplication). PCLMULQDQ is the
    enabler for AES-GCM hardware acceleration; the AES-GCM AEAD module
    queries this flag to choose between the carry-less-multiply GHASH
    fast path and the bit-by-bit constant-time GHASH fallback.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Executes CPUID leaf 1; PCLMULQDQ present iff (ecx >> 1) & 1 == 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    ~100 cycles. Identical cost profile to aes_supports_hardware_acceleration.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No secret-dependent control flow. CPUID output is a public CPU
    property.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # CPUID leaf 1: PCLMULQDQ bit = ECX bit 1
        mov rax, 1
        cpuid
        shr rcx, 1
        and rcx, 1
        mov [rbp-8], rcx
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constant-time byte equality (returns 0xFF if equal, 0x00 if not)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_ct_eq_mask" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time byte equality: returns 0xFF if (a & 0xFF) == (b & 0xFF),
    otherwise 0x00. Used as the per-candidate selector mask in the
    full-S-box-scan SubBytes implementation. The output mask can be
    AND-ed against a candidate byte to select-or-zero.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Mask both inputs to byte width.
    2. d = a_byte XOR b_byte. d is 0 iff equal, else in [1, 255].
    3. neg = 0 - d. In two's complement, neg has bit 63 set iff d != 0.
    4. or_val = d OR neg. Bit 63 of or_val is set iff d != 0.
    5. shifted = or_val shifted right by 63. (Logical shift in Runa
       yields 0 or 1.)
    6. not_eq = shifted AND 1.
    7. eq_bit = 1 - not_eq.
    8. mask = eq_bit multiplied by 255. Yields 0xFF if equal, 0 otherwise.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight 64-bit ALU operations. Sub-nanosecond on any modern CPU.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. No branches.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let am be a bitwise_and 255
    Let bm be b bitwise_and 255
    Let d be am bitwise_xor bm
    Let neg_d be 0 minus d
    Let or_val be d bitwise_or neg_d
    Let shifted be or_val shifted right by 63
    Let not_eq be shifted bitwise_and 1
    Let eq_bit be 1 minus not_eq
    Return eq_bit multiplied by 255
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: S-box and inverse S-box table initialization
Note: Tables are written byte-by-byte into a caller-provided arena buffer.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_fill_sbox" takes sbox as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Initializes the 256-byte S-box table at the given pointer with the
    Rijndael forward S-box per FIPS 197 figure 7. The table is read-only
    after initialization; the same 256 bytes are scanned for every
    SubBytes invocation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Writes the 256 hardcoded byte values from FIPS 197 figure 7 in
    row-major order. The table is a precomputed image of the affine
    transformation composed with multiplicative inversion in GF(2^8)
    with 0 mapping to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    256 byte stores. Run once per encryption operation in this CT
    implementation. Negligible relative to the per-block scan cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public table. No secret data involved.
    @End Security_Scope

