Note: ============================================================================
Note: Constant-time S-box lookup: scans ALL 256 entries every call.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_sub_byte_ct" takes sbox as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time S-box lookup. Reads ALL 256 bytes of the sbox table
    every call and uses arithmetic equality masks to select the entry
    at the requested index. This defeats cache-timing attacks on the
    S-box (Bernstein, 2005), at the cost of 256 memory loads per
    SubByte operation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    accumulator = 0
    For i in 0..256:
        candidate = sbox[i]
        mask = aes_ct_eq_mask(i, value)        Note: 0xFF if i==value else 0
        accumulator = accumulator OR (candidate AND mask)
    Return accumulator.

    Exactly one iteration's mask is 0xFF, all others 0x00, so the
    accumulator ends with sbox[value]. Every iteration reads sbox[i]
    regardless of value, equalizing cache access pattern.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    256 byte loads × ~8 ALU ops per iteration. For a single block
    encryption (16 SubBytes per round × ~10 rounds = 160 calls) this
    is on the order of 400000 ALU ops. The pure-software AES-NI
    fallback runs at ~250 cycles/byte, dominated by this loop.
    Future SIMD lowering (PSHUFB-bitsliced) brings this to <1
    cycle/byte while preserving constant-time discipline.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The same 256 memory addresses are read in the same
    order on every call regardless of the secret index.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let val_masked be value bitwise_and 255
    Let accumulator be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 256:
        Let candidate be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with sbox, i
        Let mask be proc aes_ct_eq_mask with i, val_masked
        Let masked_candidate be candidate bitwise_and mask
        Set accumulator to accumulator bitwise_or masked_candidate
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return accumulator bitwise_and 255
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GF(2^8) arithmetic for MixColumns
Note: Reduction polynomial: x^8 + x^4 + x^3 + x + 1 (0x11b)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_xtime" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Multiplies a GF(2^8) element by x (i.e., by 2) per FIPS 197
    section 4.2.1. If the high bit is 0, the result is just a left
    shift by 1. If the high bit is 1, the shift overflows and we
    must reduce by XORing with 0x1b (the reduction polynomial
    minus the leading x^8 term).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Computed in constant time:
      shifted = (value << 1) AND 0xFF
      hi_bit = (value >> 7) AND 1
      reduce_mask = -(hi_bit) AND 0x1b      Note: 0x1b if hi_bit=1, 0 if 0
      result = shifted XOR reduce_mask
    The -(hi_bit) AND 0x1b idiom selects the reduction polynomial
    conditionally without branching.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Six 64-bit ALU ops. Sub-nanosecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The conditional reduction is selected via
    arithmetic mask.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let v be value bitwise_and 255
    Let shifted be v multiplied by 2
    Set shifted to shifted bitwise_and 255
    Let hi_bit be v divided by 128
    Set hi_bit to hi_bit bitwise_and 1
    Let neg_hi be 0 minus hi_bit
    Let reduce_mask be neg_hi bitwise_and 27
    Return shifted bitwise_xor reduce_mask
End Process

Process called "aes_gmul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Multiplies two GF(2^8) elements per FIPS 197 section 4.2. Used in
    MixColumns (encrypt) and InvMixColumns (decrypt). The encrypt
    MixColumns only needs multiplication by {01}, {02}, {03}; the
    decrypt InvMixColumns needs {09}, {0b}, {0d}, {0e}. A general
    gmul handles all of these uniformly.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Russian-peasant multiplication over GF(2^8):
      result = 0
      x = a
      y = b
      For each of 8 bits:
        bit = y AND 1
        bit_mask = -(bit)        Note: 0xFF if bit=1, 0 if 0
        result XOR= (x AND bit_mask)
        x = xtime(x)
        y = y >> 1
      Return result AND 0xFF
    The conditional XOR is done via arithmetic mask: if the current
    bit of b is 1, mask is all-ones and (x AND mask) = x; otherwise
    mask is all-zeros and (x AND mask) = 0. No branches.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    8 iterations × ~6 ALU ops each = ~48 ops. Used 16 times per
    MixColumns invocation, 9-13 times per block in encryption.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. The branch on the current bit is replaced by
    arithmetic masking.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be 0
    Let x be a bitwise_and 255
    Let y be b bitwise_and 255
    Let bit_idx be 0
    While bit_idx is less than 8:
        Let bit be y bitwise_and 1
        Let bit_mask be 0 minus bit
        Set bit_mask to bit_mask bitwise_and 255
        Let contribution be x bitwise_and bit_mask
        Set result to result bitwise_xor contribution
        Set x to proc aes_xtime with x
        Set y to y divided by 2
        Set bit_idx to bit_idx plus 1
    End While
    Return result bitwise_and 255
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Rcon table accessor: Rcon[i] = x^(i-1) in GF(2^8), per FIPS 197 section 5.2
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_rcon" takes i as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the round constant byte Rcon[i] for the key expansion.
    Per FIPS 197 section 5.2, Rcon[i] = (x^(i-1), 0, 0, 0) where
    x^(i-1) is taken in GF(2^8). The low-order byte values for
    i = 1..10 are 0x01, 0x02, 0x04, 0x08, 0x10, 0x20, 0x40, 0x80,
    0x1b, 0x36. AES-256 also uses up to i=7 internal Rcon. AES-192
    uses up to i=8.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Indexed by public (round number)-driven loop counter, so this is
    NOT on the secret-dependent path. We use a direct value selector
    for the at-most-10 cases the key schedule will request.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    A handful of equality checks. Sub-nanosecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Public table; i is a public loop counter.
    @End Security_Scope

    If i is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If i is equal to 2:
        Return 2
    End If
    If i is equal to 3:
        Return 4
    End If
    If i is equal to 4:
        Return 8
    End If
    If i is equal to 5:
        Return 16
    End If
    If i is equal to 6:
        Return 32
    End If
    If i is equal to 7:
        Return 64
    End If
    If i is equal to 8:
        Return 128
    End If
    If i is equal to 9:
        Return 27
    End If
    If i is equal to 10:
        Return 54
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Key schedule: KeyExpansion per FIPS 197 section 5.2
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_key_expand_common" takes arena as Integer, key as Integer, nk as Integer, nr as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Common key expansion implementation parameterized by Nk (key
    length in 4-byte words: 4 for AES-128, 6 for AES-192, 8 for
    AES-256) and Nr (number of rounds: 10/12/14 respectively). The
    schedule output is 4*(Nr+1) words = 16*(Nr+1) bytes = 176/208/240
    bytes for the three sizes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Per FIPS 197 section 5.2:
      For i in 0..Nk:
        schedule[i] = key[i]   (each word is 4 bytes, copied verbatim)
      For i in Nk..(4*(Nr+1)):
        temp = schedule[i-1]
        If i mod Nk == 0:
          temp = SubWord(RotWord(temp)) XOR Rcon[i/Nk]
        Else if Nk > 6 AND i mod Nk == 4:    Note: AES-256 only
          temp = SubWord(temp)
        schedule[i] = schedule[i-Nk] XOR temp

    SubWord applies the constant-time S-box to each of the four bytes.
    RotWord rotates the four bytes left by one position.

    The schedule is laid out as 4-byte little-endian words at offsets
    0, 4, 8, ... in the destination buffer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(Nr+1) iterations, each performing a 4-byte XOR plus occasional
    SubWord (4 × constant-time S-box) and RotWord. The SubWord is the
    dominant cost in the schedule, ~4 × 256 byte loads per occurrence.
    The schedule runs once per encryption call; per-block AES is
    bounded by AddRoundKey + SubBytes + ShiftRows + MixColumns where
    SubBytes dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time:
    - SubWord uses the full-scan aes_sub_byte_ct.
    - RotWord is a fixed permutation, no data-dependent indexing.
    - Rcon is indexed by public loop counter.
    - The "If i mod Nk == 0" branch is on public i (loop counter), not
      on key material.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sbox be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 256
    If sbox is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc aes_fill_sbox with sbox

    Let key_bytes be nk multiplied by 4
    Let total_words be 4 multiplied by (nr plus 1)
    Let total_bytes be total_words multiplied by 4

    Note: ---- Copy initial Nk words from key into schedule ----
    Let i_byte be 0
    While i_byte is less than key_bytes:
        Let kb be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with key, i_byte
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with schedule, i_byte, kb
        Set i_byte to i_byte plus 1
    End While

    Note: ---- Generate remaining words ----
    Let word_index be nk
    While word_index is less than total_words:
        Note: temp = schedule[word_index - 1] (4 bytes at offset (word_index-1)*4)
        Let prev_off be (word_index minus 1) multiplied by 4
        Let t0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, prev_off
        Let t1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, prev_off plus 1
        Let t2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, prev_off plus 2
        Let t3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, prev_off plus 3

        Let mod_nk be word_index modulo by nk

        If mod_nk is equal to 0:
            Note: RotWord: rotate left by one byte
            Let r0 be t1
            Let r1 be t2
            Let r2 be t3
            Let r3 be t0
            Note: SubWord
            Let s0 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, r0
            Let s1 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, r1
            Let s2 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, r2
            Let s3 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, r3
            Note: XOR with Rcon[word_index / nk]
            Let rcon_idx be word_index divided by nk
            Let rc be proc aes_rcon with rcon_idx
            Set t0 to s0 bitwise_xor rc
            Set t1 to s1
            Set t2 to s2
            Set t3 to s3
        Otherwise:
            If nk is greater than 6:
                If mod_nk is equal to 4:
                    Note: AES-256 extra SubWord
                    Let q0 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, t0
                    Let q1 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, t1
                    Let q2 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, t2
                    Let q3 be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, t3
                    Set t0 to q0
                    Set t1 to q1
                    Set t2 to q2
                    Set t3 to q3
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Note: schedule[word_index] = schedule[word_index - nk] XOR temp
        Let src_off be (word_index minus nk) multiplied by 4
        Let dst_off be word_index multiplied by 4
        Let p0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, src_off
        Let p1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, src_off plus 1
        Let p2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, src_off plus 2
        Let p3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, src_off plus 3
        Let n0 be p0 bitwise_xor t0
        Let n1 be p1 bitwise_xor t1
        Let n2 be p2 bitwise_xor t2
        Let n3 be p3 bitwise_xor t3
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with schedule, dst_off, n0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with schedule, dst_off plus 1, n1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with schedule, dst_off plus 2, n2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with schedule, dst_off plus 3, n3

        Set word_index to word_index plus 1
    End While

    Return total_bytes
End Process

Process called "aes128_key_expand" takes arena as Integer, key as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    AES-128 key expansion: 16-byte key -> 176-byte schedule (11 round
    keys). Delegates to aes_key_expand_common with Nk=4, Nr=10.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls aes_key_expand_common(arena, key, 4, 10, schedule).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Run once per encryption-stream setup; cost is dominated by 10
    SubWord invocations (one per round-key word generation cycle).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (inherits the common implementation's discipline).
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If key is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If schedule is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be proc aes_key_expand_common with arena, key, AES128_NK, AES128_ROUNDS, schedule
    If rc is equal to AES128_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "aes192_key_expand" takes arena as Integer, key as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    AES-192 key expansion: 24-byte key -> 208-byte schedule (13 round
    keys). Delegates to aes_key_expand_common with Nk=6, Nr=12.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls aes_key_expand_common(arena, key, 6, 12, schedule).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Similar profile to AES-128; ~8 SubWord invocations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If key is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If schedule is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be proc aes_key_expand_common with arena, key, AES192_NK, AES192_ROUNDS, schedule
    If rc is equal to AES192_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "aes256_key_expand" takes arena as Integer, key as Integer, schedule as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    AES-256 key expansion: 32-byte key -> 240-byte schedule (15 round
    keys). Delegates to aes_key_expand_common with Nk=8, Nr=14. Note
    the extra SubWord at the (Nk=8, i mod Nk = 4) positions, per FIPS
    197 section 5.2.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Calls aes_key_expand_common(arena, key, 8, 14, schedule).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    ~13 RotWord+SubWord cycles plus ~6 plain SubWord cycles. Heavier
    than AES-128/192 but still <1ms on any modern CPU.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If key is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If schedule is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rc be proc aes_key_expand_common with arena, key, AES256_NK, AES256_ROUNDS, schedule
    If rc is equal to AES256_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AES round transformations
Note: State layout: column-major 4x4 byte matrix at state[0..15].
Note:   state[0] = s[0,0]   state[4] = s[0,1]   state[8]  = s[0,2]   state[12] = s[0,3]
Note:   state[1] = s[1,0]   state[5] = s[1,1]   state[9]  = s[1,2]   state[13] = s[1,3]
Note:   state[2] = s[2,0]   state[6] = s[2,1]   state[10] = s[2,2]   state[14] = s[2,3]
Note:   state[3] = s[3,0]   state[7] = s[3,1]   state[11] = s[3,2]   state[15] = s[3,3]
Note: Input bytes are loaded column-by-column: in[0..3] -> column 0, etc.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_add_round_key" takes state as Integer, schedule as Integer, round as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    XORs the 16-byte state with the round key at schedule[round*16..(round+1)*16].
    Used Nr+1 times per encryption (once before round 1, once at the
    end of each round 1..Nr).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Bytewise XOR loop of 16 bytes. Naturally constant-time.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    16 byte loads + 16 byte stores + 16 XORs per call.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let base be round multiplied by 16
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let s_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, i
        Let k_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with schedule, base plus i
        Let xored be s_byte bitwise_xor k_byte
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, i, xored
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_sub_bytes" takes state as Integer, sbox as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies the S-box to each of the 16 state bytes using the
    constant-time aes_sub_byte_ct lookup.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For each i in 0..16: state[i] = aes_sub_byte_ct(sbox, state[i])
    Each call is a 256-byte scan, so SubBytes is 16*256 = 4096 byte
    loads from the sbox table per round.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominant cost of AES on this software path: ~80% of the runtime.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (full S-box scan per byte).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let v be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, i
        Let sub be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with sbox, v
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, i, sub
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_inv_sub_bytes" takes state as Integer, inv_sbox as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies the inverse S-box to each state byte (decryption).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For each i in 0..16: state[i] = aes_sub_byte_ct(inv_sbox, state[i])
    Reuses the constant-time scanner with the inverse table.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same per-call cost as aes_sub_bytes.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let v be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, i
        Let sub be proc aes_sub_byte_ct with inv_sbox, v
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, i, sub
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_shift_rows" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Cyclically shifts the rows of the state per FIPS 197 section 5.1.2:
      Row 0: no shift
      Row 1: shift left by 1 (positions: 1, 5, 9, 13 -> 5, 9, 13, 1)
      Row 2: shift left by 2
      Row 3: shift left by 3
    In our column-major layout, row r occupies indices r, r+4, r+8, r+12.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read all four bytes of each row (rows 1, 2, 3) into locals, then
    write them back at the shifted positions. Row 0 is untouched.
    Permutation is fixed and public.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    12 byte loads + 12 byte stores. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (fixed permutation).
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Row 1: state[1], state[5], state[9], state[13] -> state[5], state[9], state[13], state[1]
    Let r1_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 1
    Let r1_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 5
    Let r1_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 9
    Let r1_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 13
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 1, r1_1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 5, r1_2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 9, r1_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 13, r1_0

    Note: Row 2: state[2], state[6], state[10], state[14] -> state[10], state[14], state[2], state[6]
    Let r2_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 2
    Let r2_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 6
    Let r2_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 10
    Let r2_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 14
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 2, r2_2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 6, r2_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 10, r2_0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 14, r2_1

    Note: Row 3: state[3], state[7], state[11], state[15] -> state[15], state[3], state[7], state[11]
    Let r3_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 3
    Let r3_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 7
    Let r3_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 11
    Let r3_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 15
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 3, r3_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 7, r3_0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 11, r3_1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 15, r3_2

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_inv_shift_rows" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of ShiftRows: shifts rows right by 1, 2, 3 positions
    respectively (decryption).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Inverse permutation:
      Row 1: positions 1, 5, 9, 13 receive 13, 1, 5, 9 (right rotate)
      Row 2: positions 2, 6, 10, 14 receive 10, 14, 2, 6 (2-pos right)
      Row 3: positions 3, 7, 11, 15 receive 7, 11, 15, 3 (3-pos right)
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Same as aes_shift_rows.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let r1_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 1
    Let r1_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 5
    Let r1_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 9
    Let r1_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 13
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 1, r1_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 5, r1_0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 9, r1_1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 13, r1_2

    Let r2_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 2
    Let r2_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 6
    Let r2_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 10
    Let r2_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 14
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 2, r2_2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 6, r2_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 10, r2_0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 14, r2_1

    Let r3_0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 3
    Let r3_1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 7
    Let r3_2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 11
    Let r3_3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, 15
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 3, r3_1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 7, r3_2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 11, r3_3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, 15, r3_0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_mix_columns" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies the MixColumns transformation per FIPS 197 section 5.1.3.
    Each column c of the state is treated as a polynomial over GF(2^8)
    and multiplied by the fixed polynomial {03}x^3 + {01}x^2 + {01}x + {02}
    modulo x^4 + 1. The result for column [s0, s1, s2, s3] is:
      s0' = ({02}*s0) XOR ({03}*s1) XOR s2 XOR s3
      s1' = s0 XOR ({02}*s1) XOR ({03}*s2) XOR s3
      s2' = s0 XOR s1 XOR ({02}*s2) XOR ({03}*s3)
      s3' = ({03}*s0) XOR s1 XOR s2 XOR ({02}*s3)
    where {02}*x = xtime(x) and {03}*x = x XOR xtime(x).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterate over the 4 columns. For each, load the 4 input bytes,
    compute the 4 output bytes via xtime, and store back.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    4 columns × (~8 xtime + ~16 XOR) = ~96 ops per call.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (all GF arithmetic is CT).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let col be 0
    While col is less than 4:
        Let base be col multiplied by 4
        Let s0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base
        Let s1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 1
        Let s2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 2
        Let s3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 3

        Let t0 be proc aes_xtime with s0
        Let t1 be proc aes_xtime with s1
        Let t2 be proc aes_xtime with s2
        Let t3 be proc aes_xtime with s3

        Note: m_ij = {03}*s_j = s_j XOR xtime(s_j)
        Let m0 be t0 bitwise_xor s0
        Let m1 be t1 bitwise_xor s1
        Let m2 be t2 bitwise_xor s2
        Let m3 be t3 bitwise_xor s3

        Note: s0' = t0 XOR m1 XOR s2 XOR s3 = (xtime(s0)) XOR (s1 XOR xtime(s1)) XOR s2 XOR s3
        Let n0 be t0 bitwise_xor m1
        Set n0 to n0 bitwise_xor s2
        Set n0 to n0 bitwise_xor s3

        Let n1 be s0 bitwise_xor t1
        Set n1 to n1 bitwise_xor m2
        Set n1 to n1 bitwise_xor s3

        Let n2 be s0 bitwise_xor s1
        Set n2 to n2 bitwise_xor t2
        Set n2 to n2 bitwise_xor m3

        Let n3 be m0 bitwise_xor s1
        Set n3 to n3 bitwise_xor s2
        Set n3 to n3 bitwise_xor t3

        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base, n0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 1, n1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 2, n2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 3, n3

        Set col to col plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_inv_mix_columns" takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Applies the InvMixColumns transformation per FIPS 197 section 5.3.3.
    Each column is multiplied by the polynomial
    {0b}x^3 + {0d}x^2 + {09}x + {0e}, the inverse of MixColumns
    polynomial modulo x^4 + 1. The result for [s0, s1, s2, s3] is:
      s0' = ({0e}*s0) XOR ({0b}*s1) XOR ({0d}*s2) XOR ({09}*s3)
      s1' = ({09}*s0) XOR ({0e}*s1) XOR ({0b}*s2) XOR ({0d}*s3)
      s2' = ({0d}*s0) XOR ({09}*s1) XOR ({0e}*s2) XOR ({0b}*s3)
      s3' = ({0b}*s0) XOR ({0d}*s1) XOR ({09}*s2) XOR ({0e}*s3)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    For each column, compute the four products via aes_gmul (a fully
    general GF(2^8) multiplier) and XOR them.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    4 columns × (16 gmul + 12 XOR) ~ 4*144 ops = ~600 ops per call.
    Heavier than MixColumns, hence why the decryption hot path can be
    accelerated by precomputing equivalent inverse tables; we don't
    do that here because the additional cache footprint is undesirable
    on the constant-time path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time (aes_gmul is CT).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let col be 0
    While col is less than 4:
        Let base be col multiplied by 4
        Let s0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base
        Let s1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 1
        Let s2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 2
        Let s3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, base plus 3

        Let e0 be proc aes_gmul with 14, s0
        Let b1 be proc aes_gmul with 11, s1
        Let d2 be proc aes_gmul with 13, s2
        Let n9_3 be proc aes_gmul with 9, s3
        Let n0 be e0 bitwise_xor b1
        Set n0 to n0 bitwise_xor d2
        Set n0 to n0 bitwise_xor n9_3

        Let n9_0 be proc aes_gmul with 9, s0
        Let e1 be proc aes_gmul with 14, s1
        Let b2 be proc aes_gmul with 11, s2
        Let d3 be proc aes_gmul with 13, s3
        Let n1 be n9_0 bitwise_xor e1
        Set n1 to n1 bitwise_xor b2
        Set n1 to n1 bitwise_xor d3

        Let d0 be proc aes_gmul with 13, s0
        Let n9_1 be proc aes_gmul with 9, s1
        Let e2 be proc aes_gmul with 14, s2
        Let b3 be proc aes_gmul with 11, s3
        Let n2 be d0 bitwise_xor n9_1
        Set n2 to n2 bitwise_xor e2
        Set n2 to n2 bitwise_xor b3

        Let b0 be proc aes_gmul with 11, s0
        Let d1 be proc aes_gmul with 13, s1
        Let n9_2 be proc aes_gmul with 9, s2
        Let e3 be proc aes_gmul with 14, s3
        Let n3 be b0 bitwise_xor d1
        Set n3 to n3 bitwise_xor n9_2
        Set n3 to n3 bitwise_xor e3

        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base, n0
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 1, n1
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 2, n2
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, base plus 3, n3

        Set col to col plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Block encryption / decryption (public API)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_encrypt_block_common" takes arena as Integer, schedule as Integer, nr as Integer, in_block as Integer, out_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encrypts one 16-byte block using a precomputed key schedule. The
    same routine handles AES-128/192/256 by parameterizing the round
    count Nr.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Load the 16 plaintext bytes into a local state buffer.
    2. Initial AddRoundKey with round-key 0.
    3. For round r in 1..(Nr-1): SubBytes, ShiftRows, MixColumns, AddRoundKey(r).
    4. Final round (Nr): SubBytes, ShiftRows, AddRoundKey(Nr).
    5. Store the 16-byte state into out_block.

    A 256-byte S-box scratch is allocated in the arena and initialized
    once per call. In a high-throughput stream context the caller can
    amortize this by pre-populating an S-box and calling the lower-level
    primitives directly; the public API guarantees a self-contained call.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Dominated by SubBytes (Nr * 16 calls to aes_sub_byte_ct, each a
    256-byte scan). For AES-128 that is 160 scans * 256 loads = 40960
    byte loads from the S-box per block. AES-NI hardware replaces all
    of this with a handful of AESENC instructions per round (~5
    cycles); software is ~250 cycles/byte.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time throughout. No secret-dependent branches or memory
    accesses on any internal helper.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 16
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sbox be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 256
    If sbox is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc aes_fill_sbox with sbox

    Note: Load plaintext into state
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with in_block, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, i, b
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initial round key
    proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, 0

    Note: Rounds 1 .. Nr-1
    Let round be 1
    While round is less than nr:
        proc aes_sub_bytes with state, sbox
        proc aes_shift_rows with state
        proc aes_mix_columns with state
        proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, round
        Set round to round plus 1
    End While

    Note: Final round (no MixColumns)
    proc aes_sub_bytes with state, sbox
    proc aes_shift_rows with state
    proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, nr

    Note: Store
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than 16:
        Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, j
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_block, j, b2
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "aes_decrypt_block_common" takes arena as Integer, schedule as Integer, nr as Integer, in_block as Integer, out_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decrypts one 16-byte block using a precomputed key schedule. The
    same routine handles AES-128/192/256 by parameterizing Nr.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Load ciphertext into state.
    2. Initial AddRoundKey with round-key Nr.
    3. For round r in (Nr-1)..1 (descending):
         InvShiftRows, InvSubBytes, AddRoundKey(r), InvMixColumns.
    4. Final round (r=0): InvShiftRows, InvSubBytes, AddRoundKey(0).
    5. Store state.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Slower than encryption because InvMixColumns uses general gmul
    rather than xtime. Same overall constant-time discipline.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time throughout.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let state be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 16
    If state is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let inv_sbox be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, 256
    If inv_sbox is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc aes_fill_inv_sbox with inv_sbox

    Note: Load ciphertext
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with in_block, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with state, i, b
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initial AddRoundKey with round Nr
    proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, nr

    Note: Rounds Nr-1 .. 1
    Let round be nr minus 1
    While round is greater than 0:
        proc aes_inv_shift_rows with state
        proc aes_inv_sub_bytes with state, inv_sbox
        proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, round
        proc aes_inv_mix_columns with state
        Set round to round minus 1
    End While

    Note: Final round
    proc aes_inv_shift_rows with state
    proc aes_inv_sub_bytes with state, inv_sbox
    proc aes_add_round_key with state, schedule, 0

    Note: Store
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than 16:
        Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with state, j
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with out_block, j, b2
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public API: dispatch by schedule size
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "aes_encrypt_block" takes arena as Integer, schedule as Integer, schedule_size as Integer, in_block as Integer, out_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public block-encryption entry point. The caller passes the
    precomputed schedule along with its size (176, 208, or 240 bytes)
    so the routine can infer the round count Nr.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    schedule_size 176 -> Nr=10 (AES-128)
    schedule_size 208 -> Nr=12 (AES-192)
    schedule_size 240 -> Nr=14 (AES-256)
    Any other value is rejected.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single block invocation; overhead is a couple of branches plus the
    block computation itself.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. Schedule-size dispatch is on a public value.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If schedule is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If in_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If out_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If schedule_size is equal to AES128_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_encrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES128_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    If schedule_size is equal to AES192_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_encrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES192_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    If schedule_size is equal to AES256_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_encrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES256_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "aes_decrypt_block" takes arena as Integer, schedule as Integer, schedule_size as Integer, in_block as Integer, out_block as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Public block-decryption entry point. Mirrors aes_encrypt_block.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Dispatches on schedule_size to choose Nr, then calls
    aes_decrypt_block_common.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single block invocation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    If arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If schedule is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If in_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If out_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If schedule_size is equal to AES128_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_decrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES128_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    If schedule_size is equal to AES192_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_decrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES192_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    If schedule_size is equal to AES256_SCHEDULE_SIZE:
        Return proc aes_decrypt_block_common with arena, schedule, AES256_ROUNDS, in_block, out_block
    End If
    Return 0
End Process
